You have a Python script that you want to run automatically at a specific time. You want to use a cron job to schedule this task, but you're not sure how to set up the cron job in your Linux or Mac OS X system.

To set up a cron job in Linux or Mac OS X, you need to follow these steps:

1. Open the crontab editor by running the following command:

$ crontab -e

2. Add the following line to the crontab file:

30 2 * * * /path/to/your/python/script

This line specifies that the script should run at 2:30 AM every day. The * means that the script should run on all days of the week. The * * * * means that the script should run as a normal user, not as root.

Once you've added the line to the crontab file, you need to save the file and exit the editor. The cron job will now be scheduled to run automatically at the specified time.